7 ExprInfo a_bounds, b_bounds;

11 if (bounds && no_overflow_int(op->type)) {

13 // cancellation rule that exploits that should always
14 // remutate to recalculate the bounds.

16 bounds->max_defined = a_bounds.max_defined && b_bounds.min_defined;
17 if (sub_would_overflow(64, a_bounds.min, b_bounds.max)) {
18 bounds->min_defined = false;
19 bounds->min = 0;
20 } else {
21 bounds->min = a_bounds.min - b_bounds.max;
22 }

26 } else {
27 bounds->max = a_bounds.max - b_bounds.min;
28 }

277 // When you have min(x, y) - min(z, w) and no further
278 // information, there are four possible ways for the
279 // mins to resolve. However if you can prove that the
280 // decisions are correlated (i.e. x < y implies z < w or
281 // vice versa), then there are simplifications to be
282 // made that tame x. Whether or not these
283 // simplifications are profitable depends on what terms
284 // end up being constant.
285
286 // If x < y implies z < w:
287 // min(x, y) - min(z, w)
288 // = min(x - min(z, w), y - min(z, w)) using the distributive properties of min/max
289 // = min(x - z, y - min(z, w)) using the implication
290 // This duplicates z, so it's good if x - z causes some cancellation (e.g. they are equal)
291
292 // If, on the other hand, z < w implies x < y:
293 // min(x, y) - min(z, w)
294 // = max(min(x, y) - z, min(x, y) - w) using the distributive properties of min/max
295 // = max(x - z, min(x, y) - w) using the implication
296 // Again, this is profitable when x - z causes some cancellation
297
298 // What follows are special cases of this general
299 // transformation where it is easy to see that x - z
300 // cancels and that there is an implication in one
301 // direction or the other.
302
303 // Then the actual rules. We consider only cases where x and z differ by a constant.
